{"status":"OK","result":{"originalLocale":"en","allowViewHistory":true,"creationTimeSeconds":1435136177,"rating":9,"authorHandle":"gkeesh7","modificationTimeSeconds":1435137426,"id":18833,"title":"\u003cp\u003eGeometry Problem \u003c/p\u003e","locale":"en","content":"\u003cdiv class\u003d\"ttypography\"\u003e\u003cp\u003eGreetings Everyone,\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eI was doing the maximum enclosing circle problem, This is the subproblem of that.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eGiven two ends points of a common chord of two circles of equal radius say \u003cstrong\u003eR\u003c/strong\u003e find out the coordinates of two centers of the circles (without much precision loss preferably)\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eThe condition can be pictorially represented like.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cimg alt\u003d\" \" src\u003d\"/predownloaded/cc/6b/cc6b0c1a1826c315a26fca66f818e21ba24e6e89.png\" style\u003d\"max-width: 100.0%;max-height: 100.0%;\" /\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eA possible solution might be to find the coordinates of mid point of \u003cspan class\u003d\"tex-span\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eA\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/span\u003e and \u003cspan class\u003d\"tex-span\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eB\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/span\u003e that is \u003cspan class\u003d\"tex-span\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eM\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/span\u003e which is \u003cimg align\u003d\"middle\" class\u003d\"tex-formula\" src\u003d\"/predownloaded/11/6d/116d80a84278b6dd0ccb244d89647398389237f3.png\" style\u003d\"max-width: 100.0%;max-height: 100.0%;\" /\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eSince the slope of line joining \u003cspan class\u003d\"tex-span\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eA\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/span\u003e and \u003cspan class\u003d\"tex-span\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eB\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/span\u003e is \u003cimg align\u003d\"middle\" class\u003d\"tex-formula\" src\u003d\"/predownloaded/87/ab/87abeb3b5c0238f3bd843659bbcdcd67c08b3828.png\" style\u003d\"max-width: 100.0%;max-height: 100.0%;\" /\u003e and since the line joining the centers would be perpendicular to the slope of line joining \u003cspan class\u003d\"tex-span\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eC\u003c/i\u003e1\u003c/span\u003e and \u003cspan class\u003d\"tex-span\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eC\u003c/i\u003e2\u003c/span\u003e would be \u003cimg align\u003d\"middle\" class\u003d\"tex-formula\" src\u003d\"/predownloaded/66/43/66436182306b45f195e69da256d9a364cf3f0555.png\" style\u003d\"max-width: 100.0%;max-height: 100.0%;\" /\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eThe distance between the points \u003cspan class\u003d\"tex-span\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eM\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/span\u003e and \u003cspan class\u003d\"tex-span\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eC\u003c/i\u003e1\u003c/span\u003e or \u003cspan class\u003d\"tex-span\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eC\u003c/i\u003e2\u003c/span\u003e can be found using pythagoras theorem i.e. \u003cimg align\u003d\"middle\" class\u003d\"tex-formula\" src\u003d\"/predownloaded/88/03/88036963f754c010ad3f7b7ee5f4791993546b56.png\" style\u003d\"max-width: 100.0%;max-height: 100.0%;\" /\u003e where \u003cimg align\u003d\"middle\" class\u003d\"tex-formula\" src\u003d\"/predownloaded/cf/a4/cfa4b2a77535a60029abce3977bbab9c45f82cd7.png\" style\u003d\"max-width: 100.0%;max-height: 100.0%;\" /\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eNow since we know the slope of the line and a point on it and distance between the points we can now find the coordinates of centers, but It\u0027s highly insensitive to precision.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eAny other method, resource , links etc would be deeply appreciated.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eThanks in advance.\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e","tags":["geometry","computational geometry","math"]}}